    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement occurs when two or more particles become linked so that the state of one instantly influences the other, regardless of the distance separating them. This differs from classical correlation because classical correlations only arise when particles already share a hidden, pre-determined state, whereas entangled particles have no definite state until measured. Crucially, quantum entanglement defies \"local realism,\" meaning there is no underlying local variable setting both particles in advance; their outputs are fundamentally random but perfectly correlated in ways that classical physics cannot explain.",
